# Project Architecture

This document defines the architecture of the LexMastery Flutter application.

This architecture is mandatory.

Never introduce architectural patterns that conflict with this document.

---

# Architecture Philosophy

LexMastery uses

Feature-First Modular Clean Architecture.

The application is divided into independent business features.

Each feature owns its

UI

Business Logic

Data

Routing

Dependencies

Testing

A feature should be understandable in isolation.

---

# Architectural Layers

Every feature follows

Presentation

↓

Domain

↓

Data

↓

External Services

Dependencies only flow downward.

Presentation must never depend on Data.

Data must never depend on Presentation.

---

# Presentation Layer

Responsible for

UI

Widgets

Controllers

State

Navigation

Animations

Validation feedback

Presentation MUST NOT

call APIs

contain business logic

parse JSON

contain SQL

---

# Domain Layer

Contains

Entities

Use Cases

Repository Interfaces

Business Rules

Domain must never depend on Flutter.

Domain should remain pure Dart.

---

# Data Layer

Contains

DTOs

Repositories

Datasource

API Clients

Local Cache

Serialization

The Data layer translates external data into Domain objects.

---

# Core Module

The Core module contains shared infrastructure.

Examples

Networking

Theme

Navigation

Analytics

Storage

Logging

Utilities

Dependency registration

Error models

Core should not contain feature logic.

---

# Shared Module

Shared contains reusable UI.

Examples

Buttons

Cards

Dialogs

Inputs

Icons

Spacing

Typography

Extensions

Shared Widgets

A shared component should only exist if reused by at least three features.

Otherwise keep it inside the feature.

---

# Features

Every business capability belongs inside a Feature.

Examples

authentication

onboarding

dashboard

courses

quizzes

flashcards

ai_tutor

diagnostics

analytics

profile

settings

notifications

---

# Feature Independence

A feature should not import another feature directly.

Communication happens through

Repositories

Interfaces

Core Services

Events

Never create circular dependencies.

---

# Dependency Direction

Allowed

Presentation

↓

Domain

↓

Data

↓

Core

Forbidden

Data

↓

Presentation

Feature A

↓

Feature B

Presentation

↓

Presentation

---

# Widgets

Widgets should remain small.

Prefer

Stateless Widgets

Consumer Widgets

Small compositions

Avoid massive build methods.

---

# Controllers

Each screen owns one Controller.

Controllers coordinate

UI state

Use Cases

Repositories

Navigation

Controllers never contain rendering logic.

---

# Use Cases

Every meaningful business action becomes a Use Case.

Examples

LoginUser

FetchDashboard

GenerateStudyPlan

SubmitAssessment

StartQuiz

CompleteLesson

Never place business rules inside Controllers.

---

# Repositories

Repositories expose business operations.

Controllers never know whether data comes from

REST

Cache

Offline Storage

Mock

Repository handles that complexity.

---

# Data Sources

Split Data Sources.

Remote

REST API

Local

Hive

Secure Storage

Memory Cache

Repositories coordinate both.

---

# DTOs

DTOs exist only in Data.

Entities exist only in Domain.

Never expose DTOs to UI.

---

# Models

Always immutable.

Always generated using Freezed.

Never mutate state.

---

# Routing

Each feature owns its routes.

Global routing lives inside Core.

Features register routes.

Do not centralize feature logic inside routing.

---

# Themes

One global theme.

No feature should create its own ThemeData.

Use Theme Extensions.

---

# Assets

Assets belong in

assets/

Never inside features.

---

# Localization

Every feature supports localization.

Never hardcode strings.

---

# Analytics

Every feature should expose analytics events.

Analytics lives in Core.

Never call Firebase directly from features.

---

# Logging

Logging lives in Core.

Features log through interfaces.

---

# Authentication

Authentication belongs to the Authentication feature.

Other features should never manage authentication state.

---

# Networking

Networking belongs inside Core.

Features never configure Dio.

---

# Design System

Every feature uses the Design System.

Never hardcode

Colors

Spacing

Radius

Typography

Elevation

Everything comes from Design Tokens.

---

# Reusability Rule

Before creating a Widget

Search existing Widgets.

Before creating a Repository

Search existing Repositories.

Before creating a Service

Search existing Services.

Never duplicate.

---

# Folder Ownership

Every file has one owner.

One feature owns one responsibility.

Never place unrelated code together.

---

# Cursor Instructions

When generating any code:

1.

Identify the Feature.

2.

Identify the Layer.

3.

Identify dependencies.

4.

Reuse existing architecture.

5.

Generate production-quality implementation.

If uncertain,

prefer the existing architecture over creating new patterns.

Architecture consistency is more important than implementation speed.